1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,315
-Who doesn't love Anne Hathaway? Thank you for coming.

2
00:00:02,315 --> 00:00:06,961
-That's very nice. But you know when you have a moment, you're just like, "Oh, I'm gonna remember that forever." Thank you so much for that.

3
00:00:06,961 --> 00:00:11,929
-There you go. It just happened. Come on. The Roots.

4
00:00:11,929 --> 00:00:14,697
-Thank you for playing "Reverse Charades" with me. You're a great partner.

5
00:00:14,697 --> 00:00:19,230
-I mean, are you competitive when you play games? Do you play games at home?

6
00:00:19,230 --> 00:00:20,503
-Oh, I don't mean to be.

7
00:00:20,503 --> 00:00:21,297
-I know. Me neither.

8
00:00:21,297 --> 00:00:24,153
-I don't mean to be. But then you saw her over there, I was like, "No, it's just a nice, friendly game."

9
00:00:24,153 --> 00:00:27,328
-And then the last, I'm like, "But the points are on. Like, it's on."

10
00:00:27,328 --> 00:00:28,612
-Let's go. I want to win this.

11
00:00:28,612 --> 00:00:32,835
-Something takes over. I'm less competitive now.

12
00:00:32,835 --> 00:00:39,413
-I think maybe being competitive is genetic, because my kids are, like – They're competitive, too.

13
00:00:39,413 --> 00:00:43,262
-And it turns out motherhood has softened me, and I like to watch them win.

14
00:00:43,262 --> 00:00:50,164
-My kids are very competitive, too. Well, my one daughter is. Yeah. Yeah. The other one doesn't really care.

15
00:00:50,164 --> 00:00:51,845
-She's like, "That's fun. It's all good."

16
00:00:51,845 --> 00:00:53,234
-But the other one really wants to win.

17
00:00:53,234 --> 00:01:01,599
-And I don't throw the games. You know, I go – I really – And I play for – I play for money, too.

18
00:01:01,599 --> 00:01:05,037
-Are you – Is there a party game that you're especially good at?

19
00:01:05,037 --> 00:01:14,073
-No. I mean, you know, I was playing a game – We play a lot of Pokémon and we play a lot of Trouble and Sorry!

20
00:01:14,073 --> 00:01:19,345
-But there is a game – I was working last week and I was on set, and we were just passing the time.

21
00:01:19,345 --> 00:01:26,426
-And have you seen that movie trivia game where it's cards and they just asks you questions?

22
00:01:26,426 --> 00:01:30,565
-And I was just having one of those, like, runs where I couldn't miss.

23
00:01:30,565 --> 00:01:32,739
-Like, I just knew and I was, like, surprising myself.

24
00:01:32,739 --> 00:01:34,912
-Well, you know your stuff. You know movies.

25
00:01:34,912 --> 00:01:35,833
-I didn't – I mean, apparently, I do.

26
00:01:35,833 --> 00:01:43,552
-And then I got to this one question, and they were like, "Oh, okay. So, uh, junior executive assistant, 'Devil Wears Prada.'"

27
00:01:43,552 --> 00:02:00,150
-I'm just like, "Emily Blunt." And they were like, "No." And it wasn't her. It was me.

28
00:02:00,150 --> 00:02:05,768
-Do you ever – Do you kind of do a project and then you kind of block it out of your mind or no?

29
00:02:05,768 --> 00:02:07,500
-You just – It just so happens you…

30
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:09,813
-I don't know. I'm not huge on looking back.

31
00:02:09,813 --> 00:02:18,074
-It is kind of funny when – Like, because, you know, I was in this movie when I was 17 years old called "The Princess Diaries."

32
00:02:18,074 --> 00:02:22,980
-I watch you all the time. To this day, I watch you all the time.

33
00:02:22,980 --> 00:02:23,413
-It must be your girls.

34
00:02:23,413 --> 00:02:26,029
-We love you. Yeah, they love you so much.

35
00:02:26,029 --> 00:02:29,229
-I love that it's become kind of one of those family touchstones.

36
00:02:29,229 --> 00:02:33,121
-So, anyway, people quote it to me all the time, and I don't know what they're talking about.

37
00:02:33,121 --> 00:02:34,544
-I haven't seen it in a minute.

38
00:02:34,544 --> 00:02:39,502
-But "Devil Wears Prada" – I recently saw a photo of you and Anna Wintour.

39
00:02:39,502 --> 00:02:45,853
-You made your kind of Broadway debut together in "Gutenberg! The Musical!"

40
00:02:45,853 --> 00:02:48,342
-Did the crowd go nuts?

41
00:02:48,342 --> 00:02:54,264
-So, they – So, by the way, I have to say, that's Josh Gad and that's Andrew Rannells.

42
00:02:54,264 --> 00:02:54,996
-They're both dear friends.

43
00:02:54,996 --> 00:02:58,693
-And they're so – They were so brilliant in the show. It was really next level.

44
00:02:58,693 --> 00:03:02,971
-And at the end of the show, they invite two people up onstage.

45
00:03:02,971 --> 00:03:06,437
-And, so, they said my name first, and the audience had a very nice reaction.

46
00:03:06,437 --> 00:03:10,795
-And then they said Anna's name, and it was like rock star.

47
00:03:10,795 --> 00:03:14,523
-Because you don't really see Anna do many things that are outside of her –

48
00:03:14,523 --> 00:03:15,504
-Wear a trucker hat.

49
00:03:15,504 --> 00:03:20,669
-Yes, exactly. You'd never see Anna Wintour, from Vogue, wear a trucker hat.

50
00:03:20,669 --> 00:03:23,408
-But everyone just went nuts. She's also a New York icon.

51
00:03:23,408 --> 00:03:28,786
-She's a worldwide icon.

52
00:03:28,786 --> 00:03:29,650
-She's everything.

53
00:03:29,650 --> 00:03:31,260
-Is she fun to share the stage with?

54
00:03:31,260 --> 00:03:36,906
-Yeah. Yeah, really, really fun. And just – She's been incredibly sweet to me.

55
00:03:36,906 --> 00:03:40,742
-And I'm very – I'm just very grateful for our relationship.

56
00:03:40,742 --> 00:03:42,852
-Do you get nervous around – I get a little nervous –

57
00:03:42,852 --> 00:03:43,567
-I absolutely do.

58
00:03:43,567 --> 00:03:48,957
-You do? Now, I have less to lose, because I'm never going to be on the cover of Vogue, so I have nothing to worry about.

59
00:03:48,957 --> 00:03:53,841
-But she likes me, and we've been friends for a long time, so I kind of – I'm comfy around her.

60
00:03:53,841 --> 00:03:56,541
-I try to keep it comfy. I try to keep it cozy.

61
00:03:56,541 --> 00:04:07,432
-But inside, my heart is – I just respect her so much.

62
00:04:07,432 --> 00:04:12,295
-I got the respect and also the dig at the same time. So it was perfect.

63
00:04:12,295 --> 00:04:32,035
-That's how well I know you. That's how cozy I am.

64
00:04:32,035 --> 00:04:35,247
-I saw you, and it was at the…

65
00:04:35,247 --> 00:04:36,532
-"Twelfth Night" at the Delacorte Theater.

66
00:04:36,532 --> 00:04:41,471
-You were amazing. Do you get nervous? Does anything go wrong? Nothing went wrong when I saw you.

67
00:04:41,471 --> 00:04:42,811
-Nothing went wrong? Thank goodness.

68
00:04:42,811 --> 00:04:48,148
-Well, because – So, the Delacorte Theater is an outdoor theater in Central Park.

69
00:04:48,148 --> 00:04:50,511
-And so – And you're doing Shakespeare.

70
00:04:50,511 --> 00:04:53,360
-And it rained almost every night.

71
00:04:53,360 --> 00:05:00,427
-And so, but it's kind of amazing, because every night, the last line of the show, which we actually sang, was "for the rain, it raineth every day."

72
00:05:00,427 --> 00:05:02,703
-And so the audience, at that moment, always burst out laughing.

73
00:05:02,703 --> 00:05:04,080
-And the whole show was so joyful.

74
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:05,256
-I had such a wonderful time.

75
00:05:05,256 --> 00:05:09,436
-But one night, something – I don't know if it went wrong, but something happened.

76
00:05:09,436 --> 00:05:14,275
-And so, there's this scene. My character, Viola – she comes onto the stage.

77
00:05:14,275 --> 00:05:18,298
-And I knew that the line was funny, but I couldn't figure out how to make it funny.

78
00:05:18,298 --> 00:05:22,139
-So every night, I was just trying something, just anything I could think of.

79
00:05:22,139 --> 00:05:26,113
-And I was, you know, go out there, audience wouldn't laugh, and I was like, "Tomorrow."

80
00:05:26,113 --> 00:05:31,688
-And then, one night, I went out there and I said the line, and just the house went down.

81
00:05:31,688 --> 00:05:32,239
-You killed it.

82
00:05:32,239 --> 00:05:36,633
-Killed. And I was like, "Oh, I found it. This is such a good feeling."

83
00:05:36,633 --> 00:05:40,559
-And so then, of course, I leaned into it, because you do.

84
00:05:40,559 --> 00:05:43,626
-And so I lean into it and I'm just – The audience is losing their minds.

85
00:05:43,626 --> 00:05:45,625
-I look under the wings, the cast is losing their minds.

86
00:05:45,625 --> 00:05:48,143
-I'm high-fiving myself in my head.

87
00:05:48,143 --> 00:05:50,516
-I'm just like, "I've arrived. This is happening."

88
00:05:50,516 --> 00:05:53,178
-And I get offstage and I'm just like, "Well…"

89
00:05:53,178 --> 00:05:58,016
-And they go, "Did you see the raccoons?"

90
00:05:58,016 --> 00:05:59,939
-And I'm like, "The…what?"

91
00:05:59,939 --> 00:06:05,751
-And then they just go, "Behind you. As soon as you came onstage, a family of raccoons came out."

92
00:06:05,751 --> 00:06:10,792
-They were so cute. Couldn't focus on the scene because the raccoons were so cute.

93
00:06:10,792 --> 00:06:15,343
-So I was like, "Well, actually, high five to the raccoons."

94
00:06:15,343 --> 00:06:18,701
-See? You got to work with everybody.

95
00:06:18,701 --> 00:06:20,856
-You play well with others.

96
00:06:20,856 --> 00:06:23,728
-Let's talk about "The Idea of You." Oh, my gosh, buddy.

97
00:06:23,728 --> 00:06:26,826
-The trailer alone has gotten over 125 million views.

98
00:06:26,826 --> 00:06:29,214
-It crushed, broke the record.

99
00:06:29,214 --> 00:06:33,172
-Most-watched trailer of any streaming movie in history.

100
00:06:33,172 --> 00:06:36,272
-Can we set up what the movie's about?

101
00:06:36,272 --> 00:06:41,122
-The story is about Solène Marchand, who is a woman who lives in Silver Lake.

102
00:06:41,122 --> 00:06:46,102
-She's a gallery owner. She's a mom and she's got this really wonderful life.

103
00:06:46,102 --> 00:06:53,186
-And she unexpectedly meets the lead singer of the biggest boy band in the world, a 24-year-old young man named Hayes Campbell.

104
00:06:53,186 --> 00:06:56,196
-And he thinks she's kind of great.

105
00:06:56,196 --> 00:06:58,691
-And so the story is about how they fall in love.

106
00:06:58,691 --> 00:07:03,912
-Because you're just a mom and you're chaperoning this thing and you go to this thing and then you see this boy band.

107
00:07:03,912 --> 00:07:05,657
-I love hearing you describe my movie.

108
00:07:05,657 --> 00:07:20,077
-"Just a mom in this thing." "

109
00:07:20,077 --> 00:07:23,404
-So, my daughter is off watching St. Vincent.

110
00:07:23,404 --> 00:07:25,544
-Because she doesn't like the boy band anymore.

111
00:07:25,544 --> 00:07:26,650
-She liked them in seventh grade.

112
00:07:26,650 --> 00:07:31,246
-But, anyway, I have a backstage pass, so I'm an all-access thing.

113
00:07:31,246 --> 00:07:33,487
-I have to go to the bathroom. Somebody tells me where the trailers are.

114
00:07:33,487 --> 00:07:38,803
-I go and I walk into the wrong trailer.

115
00:07:38,803 --> 00:07:41,391
-And the rest is – High jinks ensues.

116
00:07:41,391 --> 00:07:44,995
-But remind me of the actor who plays the lead singer.

117
00:07:44,995 --> 00:07:48,355
-Nick Galitzine.&nbsp; &nbsp;-Oh, man, you guys have great chemistry.

118
00:07:48,355 --> 00:07:50,699
-Did you know when he was auditioning? You go, "Oh, this the guy."

119
00:07:50,699 --> 00:07:55,452
-Oh, yeah. Yeah, no, as soon as he – I actually burst out laughing when he walked in.

120
00:07:55,452 --> 00:07:59,537
-Because – Has anybody here read the book?

121
00:07:59,537 --> 00:08:04,595
-No, we don't read. -Well, you should. It's fabulous.

122
00:08:04,595 --> 00:08:13,430
-This is "The Tonight Show." Yeah, you want to go over to Stephen Colbert if you want to get people that read books.

123
00:08:13,430 --> 00:08:22,863
-We don't read. Lame!

124
00:08:22,863 --> 00:08:27,369
-We do Audible here. We do that. Does that count?

125
00:08:27,369 --> 00:08:31,136
-I think it's time for you to get me back.

126
00:08:31,136 --> 00:08:35,229
-Okay, so – It's based on this book.

127
00:08:35,229 --> 00:08:37,921
-Yeah. No, too late. No, too late.

128
00:08:37,921 --> 00:08:40,277
-But this is based on the big best-selling book.

129
00:08:40,277 --> 00:08:44,000
-Well, the book does have a fan following somewhere.

130
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:47,327
-And I think the book is incredible.

131
00:08:47,327 --> 00:08:49,395
-And Hayes Campbell is so beautifully written in the book.

132
00:08:49,395 --> 00:08:52,197
-And so we knew that we just really needed to find someone really special.

133
00:08:52,197 --> 00:08:55,447
-And he walked in, yeah, and I just thought, "Oh, that's Hayes Campbell."

134
00:08:55,447 --> 00:08:57,264
-And that was almost two years ago.

135
00:08:57,264 --> 00:09:13,639
-And now Nick and I have become really good friends, and, yeah, it's opened up in this beautiful way.

136
00:09:13,639 --> 00:09:16,395
-Hi again.

137
00:09:16,395 --> 00:09:20,781
-Are you a part of that ASMR community that gets off on listening to people pee?

138
00:09:20,781 --> 00:09:23,414
-No, I wasn't -Because I don't think you can just go around assuming –

139
00:09:23,414 --> 00:09:25,533
-It's actually my trailer.

140
00:09:25,533 --> 00:09:28,793
-It's not literally mine. You know, I don't own it.

141
00:09:28,793 --> 00:09:30,090
-This is your trailer?

142
00:09:30,090 --> 00:09:33,233
-Yeah, I'm in the band. We're performing on the main stage.

143
00:09:33,233 --> 00:09:39,855
-You know, I'm Hayes Campbell.&nbsp; -August Moon?&nbsp; -Yeah.

144
00:09:39,855 --> 00:09:41,998
-Well, I absolutely know who you are.

145
00:09:41,998 --> 00:09:50,799
-Anyway… I'll…

146
00:09:50,799 --> 00:09:53,757
-Yeah. Come on. You know how to do it.

147
00:09:53,757 --> 00:09:55,100
-Anne Hathaway, everybody. Anne Hathaway，

148
00:09:55,100 --> 00:09:59,030
-"The Idea of You" begins streaming on Prime Video this Thursday. 《The Idea of You》

149
00:09:59,030 --> 00:10:01,396
-We'll be right back with Melanie Lynskey.

150
00:10:01,396 --> 00:10:03,896
-Stick around, everybody.

